	doi = {10.1177/0739456X04267181},
	abstract = {This study investigates the relationship be- tween social connections and collective civic action. Measuring social capital in eight Phoenix, Arizona, neighborhoods allowed the authors to determine that in- dividuals with strong social bonding (i.e., association and trust among neighbors) are more likely to take civic action. How- ever, while social capital lessens the rela- tionship between an individual's social status and the likelihood of taking action, it does not eliminate the positive relation- ship. The analysis also suggests that bond- ing and bridging are distinct forms of social capital that have some different an- tecedents},
